-## Supervisor Recovery Rules
-
-- Treat repeated `SyntaxError`, `py_compile`, `TS1005`, `TS1109`, or `TS1128` failures as a signal to split the task into syntax-first import tests, minimal fixtures, proposal-size guards, then implementation.
-- Treat validation failures caused by missing fixture fields or missing fixture paths as fixture-first recovery, not as permission to weaken fail-closed assertions.
-- Treat fixture-discovery failures as exact-path recovery. The next retry should name the fixture path and schema keys in the selectable task instead of adding broad search logic.
-- Treat schema-shape failures in fixture validators as exact-schema recovery. The next retry should name the accepted fixture paths and keys instead of adding broad discovery or assuming alternate fixture shapes.
-- Treat bare malformed fragments such as `assert NAME None`, `confidence 1`, `confidence 1.0`, `if index list`, or `return 0.0 list[str]` as retry-stop diagnostics for the same target task until a smaller validation-first guard has passed.
-- Treat dataclass import-time failures under `importlib.util.module_from_spec` as a hard no-dataclass constraint for daemon-authored Python validator modules; use plain functions/constants/dicts instead of asking tests to alter import mechanics.
-- Treat missing sentinel constants such as `MODULE_STATUS` or `MODULE_PURPOSE` as a contract-preservation repair, not as permission to redesign validator behavior.
-- Treat a failing assertion on `validator_status()` as a sentinel-contract failure. Do not change `validator_status()` to announce implementation readiness unless the syntax-first test has first been changed by an explicit validation-first task.
-- After three failed attempts against the same task, move the broad task into Deferred Broad Items, append narrower recovery tasks, and select a different independent task if one exists.
-- When a narrower recovery task passes and directly supersedes older blocked retries, park those older retries outside checkbox form instead of leaving the board with blocked-only progress.
-- Do not let parked broad task counts prevent daemon progress when a fixture-only or validation-first `[ ]` task remains selectable.
-- Prefer deterministic fixtures and validation-only changes before adding live crawl, authenticated DevHub, browser, or network behavior.
-- Do not create private DevHub session files, auth state, traces, raw crawl output, screenshots, or downloaded documents in repair cycles.
